%N A088538 Decimal expansion of 4/Pi.
%C A088538 Average length of chord formed from two randomly chosen points on the circumference of a unit circle (see Weisstein/MathWorld link). - _Rick L. Shepherd_, Jun 19 2006
%C A088538 Suppose u(0) = 1 + i where i^2 = -1 and u(n+1) = (1/2)*(u(n) + |u(n)|). Conjecture: lim_{n -> oo} Real(u(n)) = 4/Pi. - _Yalcin Aktar_, Jul 18 2007
%C A088538 Ratio of the arc length of the cycloid for one period to the circumference of the corresponding circle rolling on a line. Thus, for any integral number n of revolutions of a circle of radius r, a point on the circle travels (4/Pi)*2*Pi*r*n = 8*r*n (while the center of the circle moves only 2*Pi*r*n). This ratio varies for partial revolutions and depends upon the initial position of the point with points nearest the line moving the slowest (see Dudeney, who explains how the tops of bicycle wheels move faster than the parts nearest the ground). - _Rick L. Shepherd_, May 05 2014
%C A088538 Average distance traveled in two steps of length 1 for a random walk in the plane starting at the origin. - _Jean-François Alcover_, Aug 04 2014
%C A088538 Ratio of the circle area to the area of a square having equal perimeters. - _Iaroslav V. Blagouchine_, May 06 2016
%C A088538 This is also the value of a special case (n=1) of an n-family of series considered by Hardy (see A278145): 1 + (1/2)*(1/2)^2 + (1/3)*(1*3/(2*4))^2 + (1/4)*((1*3*5) / (2*4*6))^2 + ... = Sum_{k>=0} (1/(k+1))*((2*k-1)!!/(2*k)!!)^2. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Nov 14 2016
%C A088538 Minimum ratio of the area of a rectangle to one of its inscribed ellipses, or only existing ratio if the rectangle is a square and then the only inscribed ellipse is a circle. This ellipse has its semiaxes parallel to the sides of the rectangle. If a rectangle has sides of length 2a and 2b, its area is 4*a*b, while the ellipse inscribed has a and b as semiaxes, therefore its area is a*b*Pi. Thus the ratio is (4*a*b)/(a*b*Pi) = 4/Pi. - _Giovanni Zedda_, Jun 20 2019
%C A088538 The diameter of the conventional spherical earth is (4/Pi)*10000 km = 12732.395... km. - _Jean-François Alcover_, Oct 30 2021
%C A088538 From _Jianing Song_, Aug 06 2022: (Start)
%C A088538 sign(sin(x)) = (4/Pi) * Sum_{n>=0} sin((2*n+1)*x)/(2*n+1), for all x in R;
%C A088538 sign(cos(x)) = (4/Pi) * Sum_{n>=0} (-1)^n*cos((2*n+1)*x)/(2*n+1), for all x in R. (End)
