%F A088538 4/Pi = Product_(1-(-1)^((p-1)/2)/p) where p runs through the odd primes.
%F A088538 Arcsin x = (4/Pi) Sum_{n = 1, 3, 5, 7, ...} T_n(x)/n^2 (Chebyshev series of arcsin; App C of math.CA/0403344). - _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 26 2006
%F A088538 Equals 1 + Sum_{n >= 1} ((2n-3)!!/(2n)!!)^2. [Jolley eq 274]. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 03 2011
%F A088538 Equals binomial(1,1/2). - _Bruno Berselli_, May 17 2016
%F A088538 2*A060294 (twice Buffon's constant) = 1/Gamma(3/2)^2. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Nov 14 2016
%F A088538 Equals 1 + Sum_{n>=0} (Catalan(n)/2^(2*n+1))^2, with Catalan(n) = A000108(n). This is the rewritten Jolley (274) series. See the above R. J. Mathar entry with (-1)!! := 1. - _Ralf Steiner_, Sep 18 2018
%F A088538 4/Pi = 1 + (1/4)*hypergeometric([1, 1/2, 1/2], [2, 2], 1) = hypergeometric([-1/2, -1/2], [1], 1). From the g.f. of Catalan^2 given in A001246. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Sep 18 2018
%F A088538 Equals Product_{k>=1} (1 + 1/(4*k*(k+1))). - _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 05 2020
%F A088538 From _Stefano Spezia_, Oct 26 2024: (Start)
%F A088538 4/Pi = 1 + K_{n>=1} n^2/(2*n + 1), where K is the Gauss notation for an infinite continued fraction. In the expanded form, 4/Pi = 1 + 1^2/(3 + 2^2/(5 + 3^2/(7 + 4^2/(9 + 5^2/(11 + ...))))) (see Finch at p. 23).
%F A088538 4/Pi = Sum_{n>=0} tan(Pi/2^(n+2))/2^n (see Shamos). (End)
%F A088538 4/Pi = Sum_{n >= 0} (-1)^n * mu(2*n+1)/(2*n + 1), where mu(n) is the Möbius function A008683 (see, for example, Benito et al., p. 77). - _Peter Bala_, Jan 07 2025
